{"title_page": "Chestnut-rumped heathwren", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Chestnut-rumped heathwren\n| image = Chestnut- Rumped Heathwren small fx.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite journal | author =BirdLife International | title = ''Hylacola pyrrhopygia'' | journal = [[IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume=2012 | page =e.T22704604A39302518  | year =2012 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2012-1.RLTS.T22704604A39302518.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Hylacola\n| species = pyrrhopygia\n| authority = ([[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]] & [[Thomas Horsfield|Horsfield]], 1827)\n| synonyms = *''Calamanthus pyrrhopygia pyrrhopygia'' <small>Christidis and Boles (2008)</small>\n*''Hylacola pyrrhopygius pyrrhopygius'' <small>Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993)</small>}}\nThe '''chestnut-rumped heathwren''' (''Hylacola pyrrhopygia'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]].\nIt is [[Endemism|endemic]] to temperate and subtropical forests of [[Australia]].\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren was first described by the Irish zoologist, [[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]], and [[Horsfield]], in 1827. The generic name ''Hylacola'' derives from the Greek ''hul\u0113'' 'woodland' and the Latin ''-cola'' 'dweller'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-18}}</ref> The specific epithet ''pyrrhopygia'' derives from Greek ''purrhos'' 'flame-coloured, red' and ''puge'' 'rump'.<ref name=Helm></ref> It is also known colloqiually as the scrub warbler.<ref name=Pizzey></ref>\nThere are three subspecies: ''Hylacola pyrrhopygia pyrrhopygia'' in New South Wales and Victoria; ''H. p. parkeri'' in the [[Mt Lofty Ranges]] of South Australia; and ''H. p. pedleri'' in the southern [[Flinders Ranges]] of South Australia.<ref name=Gregory>Gregory, P. (2020). \"Chestnut-rumped Heathwren (Hylacola pyrrhopygia), version 1.0.\" In ''Birds of the World'' (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, and E. de Juana, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.chrhea1.01</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren is a small bushland bird with a olive-brown back with conspicuous reddish-brown rump and tail coverts.<ref name=Simpson>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). ''Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia ISBN 067087918-5.</ref> It has a streaked brown-on-white chest and the belly and rear flanks are grey-buff.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> There is a dark subterminal band with a white tip on the usually erect tail.<ref name=Simpson></ref> Both sexes have a dull white eyebrow; eyes are yellow, while bill, legs, and feet are grey.<ref name=mdahlem>{{cite web|title=Chestnut-rumped Heathwren|url=http://www.mdahlem.net/birds/17/chrhwren.php|website=Mdahlem.net}}</ref> It measures {{convert|14|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name = \"Campbell\"/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren occurs in southeastern Australia from the [[Granite Belt]] of southeast [[Queensland]] through eastern [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria]], and southeast [[South Australia]].<ref name=Morcombe>Morcombe, Michael (2012) ''Field Guide to Australian Birds''. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. {{ISBN|978174021417-9}}</ref><ref name=birdata>{{cite web|url=https://birdata.birdlife.org.au/explore#map=-27.8587126_141.4881509_5&species_id=498|title=Birdata map:chestnut-rumped heathwren|accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> In Victoria, it ranges inland to the [[Grampians]] and [[Bendigo]] region, but is more usual in coastal parts.<ref name=Pizzey>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref> In New South Wales, it occurs inland as far as the [[Warrumbungles]] and Temora.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> Scattered populations occur in the [[Flinders Ranges|Flinders]] and [[Mt Lofty Ranges]], and the [[Fleurieu Peninsula]] of South Australia.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> Its preferred habitats are [[heath]]s of coastal, mountain and hinterland areas, and the dense undergrowth of forests and woodland.<ref>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). ''Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia {{ISBN|067087918-5}}.</ref><ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Slater>Slater, Peter (1974) ''A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines''. Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref> It is sedentary and uncommon within its range.<ref name=Morcombe></ref>\n\n==Behaviour and Breeding==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren is usually shy and secretive until the breeding season from July to November, when it will sing from a perch on a bush, though still staying partly concealed.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> Its song is a melodious \"chi-chi-tu-weet\", \"kwe-reep\" and suchlike notes in great variety, blended with mimicry of other birds.<ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Slater></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref> It also makes a harsh or scolding \"zeet\" on contact or alarm.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> The chestnut-rumped heathwren builds a domed or globular nest on or near the ground in tussocks or dense shrubs.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> It is composed of dry grass stems, bark fibre and rootlets, often appearing untidy.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> A clutch of three or four eggs is laid and usually incubated by the female.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> The eggs, measuring {{convert|20|by|15|mm|in}}, are salmon-pink, freckled with light chocolate-brown, more so at the larger end.<ref name=Pizzey></ref><ref name=Morcombe></ref>\n\n==Conservation==\nAlthough the population of chestnut heathwrens is declining,<ref name=IUCN></ref> the species is currently classified as [[least-concern species|Least Concern]] by the [[IUCN]]. However, it is listed as [[Endangered]] in South Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/files/sharedassets/public/plants_and_animals/threatened_species/pa-fact-chestnutrumpedheathwrenmountloftyranges.pdf|publisher=Natural Resources: Adelaide and Mt Lofty Ranges|title=Threatened Species Profile:Chestnut-rumped Heathwren (Mount Lofty Ranges)}}</ref> and [[Vulnerable]] in Victoria,<ref name=\"DSE2007\">{{cite book | author = Victorian Department of Sustainability and Environment | title = Advisory List of Threatened Vertebrate Fauna in Victoria - 2007 | publisher = Department of Sustainability and Environment | year = 2007 | location = East Melbourne, Victoria | pages = 15 | url = | isbn = 978-1-74208-039-0 }}</ref> with continued [[habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and [[loss of habitat]] and predation by [[introduced species|introduced]] predators being regarded as the main pressures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | refs =\n<ref name = \"Campbell\">{{cite book | title = Birds of Australia: A Photographic Guide | first = Iain | last = Campbell | first2 = Sam | last2 = Woods | first3 = Nick | last3 = Leseberg | year = 2015 | location = Princeton, NJ, US | publisher = Princeton University Press | page = 248 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wFMCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA248 | isbn = 978-0-691-15727-6}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075266}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:heathwren, chestnut-rumped}}\n[[Category:Hylacola|chestnut-rumped heathwren]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1827|chestnut-rumped heathwren]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Chestnut-rumped heathwren\n| image = Chestnut- Rumped Heathwren small fx.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite journal | author =BirdLife International | title = ''Hylacola pyrrhopygia'' | journal = [[IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume=2012 | page =e.T22704604A39302518  | year =2012 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2012-1.RLTS.T22704604A39302518.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Hylacola\n| species = pyrrhopygia\n| authority = ([[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]] & [[Thomas Horsfield|Horsfield]], 1827)\n| synonyms = *''Calamanthus pyrrhopygia pyrrhopygia'' <small>Christidis and Boles (2008)</small>\n*''Hylacola pyrrhopygius pyrrhopygius'' <small>Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993)</small>}}\nThe '''chestnut-rumped heathwren''' (''Hylacola pyrrhopygia'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]].\nIt is [[Endemism|endemic]] to temperate and subtropical forests of [[Australia]].\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren was first described by [[Vigors]] and [[Horsfield]] in 1827. The generic name ''Hylacola'' derives from the Greek ''hul\u0113'' 'woodland' and the Latin ''-cola'' 'dweller'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-18}}</ref> The specific epithet ''pyrrhopygia'' derives from Greek ''purrhos'' 'flame-coloured, red' and ''puge'' 'rump'.<ref name=Helm></ref> It is also known colloqiually as the scrub warbler.<ref name=Pizzey></ref>\nThere are three subspecies: ''Hylacola pyrrhopygia pyrrhopygia'' in New South Wales and Victoria; ''H. p. parkeri'' in the [[Mt Lofty Ranges]] of South Australia; and ''H. p. pedleri'' in the southern [[Flinders Ranges]] of South Australia.<ref name=Gregory>Gregory, P. (2020). \"Chestnut-rumped Heathwren (Hylacola pyrrhopygia), version 1.0.\" In ''Birds of the World'' (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, and E. de Juana, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.chrhea1.01</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren is a small bushland bird with a olive-brown back with conspicuous reddish-brown rump and tail coverts.<ref name=Simpson>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). ''Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia ISBN 067087918-5.</ref> It has a streaked brown-on-white chest and the belly and rear flanks are grey-buff.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> There is a dark subterminal band with a white tip on the usually erect tail.<ref name=Simpson></ref> Both sexes have a dull white eyebrow; eyes are yellow, while bill, legs, and feet are grey.<ref name=mdahlem>{{cite web|title=Chestnut-rumped Heathwren|url=http://www.mdahlem.net/birds/17/chrhwren.php|website=Mdahlem.net}}</ref> It measures {{convert|14|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name = \"Campbell\"/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren occurs in southeastern Australia from the [[Granite Belt]] of southeast [[Queensland]] through eastern [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria]], and southeast [[South Australia]].<ref name=Morcombe>Morcombe, Michael (2012) ''Field Guide to Australian Birds''. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. {{ISBN|978174021417-9}}</ref><ref name=birdata>{{cite web|url=https://birdata.birdlife.org.au/explore#map=-27.8587126_141.4881509_5&species_id=498|title=Birdata map:chestnut-rumped heathwren|accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> In Victoria, it ranges inland to the [[Grampians]] and [[Bendigo]] region, but is more usual in coastal parts.<ref name=Pizzey>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref> In New South Wales, it occurs inland as far as the [[Warrumbungles]] and Temora.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> Scattered populations occur in the [[Flinders Ranges|Flinders]] and [[Mt Lofty Ranges]], and the [[Fleurieu Peninsula]] of South Australia.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> Its preferred habitats are [[heath]]s of coastal, mountain and hinterland areas, and the dense undergrowth of forests and woodland.<ref>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). ''Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia {{ISBN|067087918-5}}.</ref><ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Slater>Slater, Peter (1974) ''A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines''. Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref> It is sedentary and uncommon within its range.<ref name=Morcombe></ref>\n\n==Behaviour and Breeding==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren is usually shy and secretive until the breeding season from July to November, when it will sing from a perch on a bush, though still staying partly concealed.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> Its song is a melodious \"chi-chi-tu-weet\", \"kwe-reep\" and suchlike notes in great variety, blended with mimicry of other birds.<ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Slater></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref> It also makes a harsh or scolding \"zeet\" on contact or alarm.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> The chestnut-rumped heathwren builds a domed or globular nest on or near the ground in tussocks or dense shrubs.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> It is composed of dry grass stems, bark fibre and rootlets, often appearing untidy.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> A clutch of three or four eggs is laid and usually incubated by the female.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> The eggs, measuring {{convert|20|by|15|mm|in}}, are salmon-pink, freckled with light chocolate-brown, more so at the larger end.<ref name=Pizzey></ref><ref name=Morcombe></ref>\n\n==Conservation==\nAlthough the population of chestnut heathwrens is declining,<ref name=IUCN></ref> the species is currently classified as [[least-concern species|Least Concern]] by the [[IUCN]]. However, it is listed as [[Endangered]] in South Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/files/sharedassets/public/plants_and_animals/threatened_species/pa-fact-chestnutrumpedheathwrenmountloftyranges.pdf|publisher=Natural Resources: Adelaide and Mt Lofty Ranges|title=Threatened Species Profile:Chestnut-rumped Heathwren (Mount Lofty Ranges)}}</ref> and [[Vulnerable]] in Victoria,<ref name=\"DSE2007\">{{cite book | author = Victorian Department of Sustainability and Environment | title = Advisory List of Threatened Vertebrate Fauna in Victoria - 2007 | publisher = Department of Sustainability and Environment | year = 2007 | location = East Melbourne, Victoria | pages = 15 | url = | isbn = 978-1-74208-039-0 }}</ref> with continued [[habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and [[loss of habitat]] and predation by [[introduced species|introduced]] predators being regarded as the main pressures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | refs =\n<ref name = \"Campbell\">{{cite book | title = Birds of Australia: A Photographic Guide | first = Iain | last = Campbell | first2 = Sam | last2 = Woods | first3 = Nick | last3 = Leseberg | year = 2015 | location = Princeton, NJ, US | publisher = Princeton University Press | page = 248 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wFMCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA248 | isbn = 978-0-691-15727-6}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075266}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:heathwren, chestnut-rumped}}\n[[Category:Hylacola|chestnut-rumped heathwren]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1827|chestnut-rumped heathwren]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaxonomy:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chestnut-rumped_heathwren"}
{"title_page": "Coupling (American TV series)", "text_new": "{{lead too short|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Coupling\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| show_name_2          = Coupling U.S.\n| genre                = [[Sitcom]]\n| based_on             = ''[[Coupling (British TV series)|Coupling]]'' by [[Steven Moffat]]\n| developer            = [[Phoef Sutton]]\n| writer               = {{Plainlist|\n* Steven Moffat\n* Paul Corrigan\n* Brad Walsh\n* Phoef Sutton\n* [[Danny Zuker]]\n* [[J. J. Philbin]]\n* Liz Astrof\n }}\n| director             = [[Andrew D. Weyman]]\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Colin Ferguson (actor)|Colin Ferguson]]\n* [[Jay Harrington]]\n* [[Christopher Moynihan]]\n* [[Lindsay Price]]\n* [[Rena Sofer]]\n* [[Sonya Walger]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \"[[Perhaps, Perhaps, Perhaps]]\"\n| composer             = [[Ralph Schuckett]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 10 (6 unaired)\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ben Silverman]]\n* Phoef Sutton\n* [[Beryl Vertue]]\n* Steven Moffat\n* [[Sue Vertue]]\n }}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Michael E. Stokes\n* Liz Astrof\n* Paul Corrigan\n* Brad Walsh\n* Robert Peacock\n}}\n| editor               = {{Plainlist|\n* Joe Bella\n* Danny White\n}}\n| camera               = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| company              = {{Plain list|\n*[[Endemol Shine North America|Reveille Productions]]\n*Mauretania Productions\n*[[Universal Television|NBC Studios]]\n*[[Universal Television]]\n}}\n| network              = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2003|9|25}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2003|10|23}}\n| related              = {{Plain list|\n*[[Coupling (British TV series)|''Coupling'' (UK)]]\n*''[[Joking Apart]]''\n}}\n| website              =\n}}\n\n'''''Coupling''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[sitcom]] television series based on the British [[Coupling (British TV series)|origional version of the same title]], which aired on [[NBC]] from September 23 to October 23, 2003.\n\n==Production==\nBy 2003, three series, or seasons, of ''Coupling'' had been broadcast on [[BBC Two]], all written by the show's creator, [[Steven Moffat]]. The show was loosely based on the beginnings of Moffat's real-life relationship with [[Sue Vertue]].<ref name=\"sysl\">{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Sternbergh |title=Selling Your Sex Life |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/07/magazine/selling-your-sex-life-139866.html?pagewanted=all |date=2003-09-07 |accessdate=2008-04-01}}</ref>\n\nNBC commissioned a remake of the show for the American market, reportedly as a replacement for ''[[Friends]]'', which was nearing the end of its run.<ref name=\"nydailynews\">{{cite news |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=17 January 2003 |title=WITH THIS SIX, YOU GET SEX Brit gang back for fun & frolic |first=David |last=BIANCULLI |page=126}}</ref> Moffat and original producers from [[Hartswood Films]], [[Sue Vertue|Sue]] and [[Beryl Vertue]], served as executive producers on the NBC adaptation, alongside [[Phoef Sutton]] and [[Ben Silverman]].<ref name=\"griffin51\">{{harvnb|Griffin|2008|p=51}}</ref>\n\nUnlike most adaptations, the NBC adaptation would reuse Moffat's original scripts, although these were adapted by Sutton and were shortened to comply with the reduced running time (NBC has multiple advertisement breaks compared to the original broadcaster, BBC Two, which has none).<ref>{{harvnb|Griffin|2008 |p=53}}</ref> Other writers, such as [[Danny Zuker]] and Paul Corrigan worked on episodes later in the series.\n\nThe original unaired [[television pilot|pilot]] starred [[Breckin Meyer]] as Jeff, [[Melissa George]] as Susan and [[Emily Rutherfurd]] as Sally. NBC then fired the writers and replaced Meyer, George and Rutherford with [[Christopher Moynihan]], [[Rena Sofer]] and [[Sonya Walger]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0549677/|title = Coupling: Season 1, Episode 0 Original Pilot (2003)|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0338592/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ql_1|title = Coupling (2003\u2013 ) Full Cast & Crew|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> George later commented that she \"dodged a bullet\" by being replaced before the show aired.<ref name=\"bullz\">{{cite web|url = http://blog.bullz-eye.com/2012/10/19/a-chat-with-melissa-george-cinemaxs-hunted/|title = The Light from the TV Shows: A Chat with Melissa George (Cinemax\u2019s \"Hunted\")|publisher = Bullz-Eye|accessdate = 19 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThirteen episodes were commissioned. However, due to poor critical reception, NBC announced the show's cancellation on October 31, after only four episodes had been broadcast. The final three planned episodes were not filmed, with the remaining six episodes unbroadcast.<ref name=\"griffin51\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nThe show received a dismal reaction from viewers and failed to perform in the ratings, being canceled before the November [[sweeps]], with six episodes remaining unaired despite heavy publicity by the network.<ref name=\"griffin51\"/> It was immediately panned as a poor imitation of the original UK series by viewers and critics. [[BBC America]] even ran commercials noting that they would play the original British versions on their station just after the American equivalent episodes on NBC aired, so that viewers could see instantly just how superior the original was. Miscasting and stilted delivery of a nearly identical script were believed to be the reasons for the failure, though creator Moffat blamed the show's failure on NBC's intervention during the creative and production processes. In 2007, he said: \"The network f--ked it up because they intervened endlessly.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=All the Pieces Matter: A Critical Analysis of HBO's \"The Wire\" |first=Todd Michael |last=Sodano |publisher=proQuest/Syracuse University |date=2008 |isbn=0549998896|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/All-pieces-matter-critical-analysis/dp/1243586982}}</ref>\n\nThe American adaptation came at a time when NBC was having success with remakes of [[BBC]] shows, such as ''[[The Weakest Link]]'' and ''[[Dog Eat Dog (game show)|Dog Eat Dog]]''. NBC would find success in 2005 with a remake of another BBC series, [[The Office (US TV series)|''The Office'']], which aired for nine seasons.\n\nBecause of what was deemed to be indecent content, two affiliates of NBC refused to air the program; [[KSL-TV]] (Channel 5) in [[Salt Lake City, Utah|Salt Lake City]], and [[WNDU-TV]] (Channel 16) in [[South Bend, Indiana]]. Both stations were owned by religious organizations, as KSL is owned by the [[Bonneville International]] division of the [[LDS Church]], while WNDU was at the time owned by a subsidiary of [[The University of Notre Dame]]. In those markets, [[The WB Television Network|WB affiliate]] [[KUCW|KUWB]] (channel 30) and a [[UPN]] [[digital subchannel]] of [[CBS]] affiliate [[WSBT-TV]] (channel 22.2, now affiliated with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]), respectively, aired the series after their network's primetime lineups, while nearby affiliates [[KENV]] (in [[Elko, Nevada]], now an affiliate of [[Comet (TV network)|Comet]]) and [[WISE-TV]] (in [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]], now a [[The CW|CW]] affiliate) aired the series in accordance with the rest of the network.\n\n[[Jeff Zucker]], former President and CEO of [[NBCUniversal]], later said of ''Coupling'' that it \"just sucked\".<ref name=\"Crupi0614\">{{cite news|last=Crupi |first=Anthony |title=Mormon Station Refuses NBC's 'The Playboy Club': Second time church-owned affiliate dumps a series |work=[[Adweek]] |date=June 14, 2011 |url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/mormon-station-refuses-nbcs-playboy-club-132502 |accessdate=October 15, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62RgV36Ak?url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/mormon-station-refuses-nbcs-playboy-club-132502 |archivedate=October 15, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{See also|Coupling (British TV series)#Characters}}\n* [[Colin Ferguson (actor)|Colin Ferguson]] as Patrick Maitland\n* [[Jay Harrington]] as Steve Taylor\n* [[Christopher Moynihan]] as Jeff Clancy\n* [[Lindsay Price]] as Jane Honda\n* [[Rena Sofer]] as Susan Freeman\n* [[Sonya Walger]] as Sally Harper\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#;\"| No.\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Written by\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Original airdate\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Prod.<br/>code\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=The Right One\n |DirectedBy=[[Andrew D. Weyman]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Steven Moffat]] (original UK episode: \"[[List of Coupling episodes#ep1|Flushed]]\")\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2003|09|25}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=Size Matters\n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=Steven Moffat (original UK episode: \"[[List of Coupling episodes#ep2|Size Matters]]\")\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2003|10|2}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=102\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Sex, Death & Nudity \n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=Steven Moffat (original UK episode: \"[[List of Coupling episodes#ep3|Sex, Death & Nudity]]\")\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2003|10|9}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=103\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=Check/Mate\n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=[[Danny Zuker]] \n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2003|10|23}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=106\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=Present Tense\n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=Paul Corrigan & Brad Walsh\n |OriginalAirDate=UNAIRED\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=104\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=A Foreign Affair\n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=''Teleplay by:''[[Phoef Sutton]] & Steven Moffat<br>Steven Moffat (original UK episode: \"[[List of Coupling episodes#ep5|The Girl with Two Breasts]]\")\n |OriginalAirDate=UNAIRED\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=105\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=Object Lessons\n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=Liz Astrof \n |OriginalAirDate=UNAIRED\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=105\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=Holiday\n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=Paul Corrigan & Brad Walsh\n |OriginalAirDate=UNAIRED\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=110\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Dressed\n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=''Teleplay by:'' Phoef Sutton & Steven Moffat<br>Steven Moffat (original UK episode: \"[[List of Coupling episodes#ep13|Dressed]]\")\n |OriginalAirDate=UNAIRED\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=108\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=Nipple Effect\n |DirectedBy=Andrew D. Weyman\n |WrittenBy=[[J.J. Philbin]]\n |OriginalAirDate=UNAIRED\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=107\n}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n*{{cite journal |year=2008 |first=Jeffrey |last=Griffin |title=Coupling Crosses the Atlantic: A Case Study in the Format Adaptation of a Fictional Series |volume=24 |\n\njournal=Warsaw Journal for the Study of the United States |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|338592|Coupling}}\n* {{Tv.com show|coupling-us|Coupling}}\n* {{Epguides|coupling_us}}\n\n[[Category:2003 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2003 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s American romantic comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American sex comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American sitcoms]]\n[[Category:American television series based on British television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series about couples]]\n[[Category:Television series by Reveille Productions]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Chicago]]\n", "text_old": "{{lead too short|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Coupling\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| show_name_2          = Coupling U.S.\n| genre                = [[Sitcom]]\n| based_on             = ''[[Coupling (British TV series)|Coupling]]'' by [[Steven Moffat]]\n| developer            = [[Phoef Sutton]]\n| writer               = {{Plainlist|\n* Steven Moffat\n* Paul Corrigan\n* Brad Walsh\n* Phoef Sutton\n* [[Danny Zuker]]\n* [[J. J. Philbin]]\n* Liz Astrof\n }}\n| director             = [[Andrew D. Weyman]]\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Colin Ferguson (actor)|Colin Ferguson]]\n* [[Jay Harrington]]\n* [[Christopher Moynihan]]\n* [[Lindsay Price]]\n* [[Rena Sofer]]\n* [[Sonya Walger]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \"[[Perhaps, Perhaps, Perhaps]]\"\n| composer             = [[Ralph Schuckett]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 10 (6 unaired)\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ben Silverman]]\n* Phoef Sutton\n* [[Beryl Vertue]]\n* Steven Moffat\n* [[Sue Vertue]]\n }}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Michael E. Stokes\n* Liz Astrof\n* Paul Corrigan\n* Brad Walsh\n* Robert Peacock\n}}\n| editor               = {{Plainlist|\n* Joe Bella\n* Danny White\n}}\n| camera               = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| company              = {{Plain list|\n*[[Endemol Shine North America|Reveille Productions]]\n*Mauretania Productions\n*[[Universal Television|NBC Studios]]\n*[[Universal Television]]\n}}\n| network              = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2003|9|25}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2003|10|23}}\n| related              = {{Plain list|\n*[[Coupling (British TV series)|''Coupling'' (UK)]]\n*''[[Joking Apart]]''\n}}\n| website              =\n}}\n\n'''''Coupling''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[sitcom]] television series based on the British [[Coupling (British TV series)|remake version of the same title]], which aired on [[NBC]] from September 23 to October 23, 2003.\n\n==Production==\nBy 2003, three series, or seasons, of ''Coupling'' had been broadcast on [[BBC Two]], all written by the show's creator, [[Steven Moffat]]. The show was loosely based on the beginnings of Moffat's real-life relationship with [[Sue Vertue]].<ref name=\"sysl\">{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Sternbergh |title=Selling Your Sex Life |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/07/magazine/selling-your-sex-life-139866.html?pagewanted=all |date=2003-09-07 |accessdate=2008-04-01}}</ref>\n\nNBC commissioned a remake of the show for the American market, reportedly as a replacement for ''[[Friends]]'', which was nearing the end of its run.<ref name=\"nydailynews\">{{cite news |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=17 January 2003 |title=WITH THIS SIX, YOU GET SEX Brit gang back for fun & frolic |first=David |last=BIANCULLI |page=126}}</ref> Moffat and original producers from [[Hartswood Films]], [[Sue Vertue|Sue]] and [[Beryl Vertue]], served as executive producers on the NBC adaptation, alongside [[Phoef Sutton]] and [[Ben Silverman]].<ref name=\"griffin51\">{{harvnb|Griffin|2008|p=51}}</ref>\n\nUnlike most adaptations, the NBC adaptation would reuse Moffat's original scripts, although these were adapted by Sutton and were shortened to comply with the reduced running time (NBC has multiple advertisement breaks compared to the original broadcaster, BBC Two, which has none).<ref>{{harvnb|Griffin|2008 |p=53}}</ref> Other writers, such as [[Danny Zuker]] and Paul Corrigan worked on episodes later in the series.\n\nThe original unaired [[television pilot|pilot]] starred [[Breckin Meyer]] as Jeff, [[Melissa George]] as Susan and [[Emily Rutherfurd]] as Sally. NBC then fired the writers and replaced Meyer, George and Rutherford with [[Christopher Moynihan]], [[Rena Sofer]] and [[Sonya Walger]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0549677/|title = Coupling: Season 1, Episode 0 Original Pilot (2003)|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0338592/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ql_1|title = Coupling (2003\u2013 ) Full Cast & Crew|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> George later commented that she \"dodged a bullet\" by being replaced before the show aired.<ref name=\"bullz\">{{cite web|url = http://blog.bullz-eye.com/2012/10/19/a-chat-with-melissa-george-cinemaxs-hunted/|title = The Light from the TV Shows: A Chat with Melissa George (Cinemax\u2019s \"Hunted\")|publisher = Bullz-Eye|accessdate = 19 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThirteen episodes were commissioned. However, due to poor critical reception, NBC announced the show's cancellation on October 31, after only four episodes had been broadcast. The final three planned episodes were not filmed, with the remaining six episodes unbroadcast.<ref name=\"griffin51\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nThe show received a dismal reaction from viewers and failed to perform in the ratings, being canceled before the November [[sweeps]], with six episodes remaining unaired despite heavy publicity by the network.<ref name=\"griffin51\"/> It was immediately panned as a poor imitation of the original UK series by viewers and critics. [[BBC America]] even ran commercials noting that they would play the original British versions on their station just after the American equivalent episodes on NBC aired, so that viewers could see instantly just how superior the original was. Miscasting and stilted delivery of a nearly identical script were believed to be the reasons for the failure, though creator Moffat blamed the show's failure on NBC's intervention during the creative and production processes. In 2007, he said: \"The network f--ked it up because they intervened endlessly.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=All the Pieces Matter: A Critical Analysis of HBO's \"The Wire\" |first=Todd Michael |last=Sodano |publisher=proQuest/Syracuse University |date=2008 |isbn=0549998896|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/All-pieces-matter-critical-analysis/dp/1243586982}}</ref>\n\nThe American adaptation came at a time when NBC was having success with remakes of [[BBC]] shows, such as ''[[The Weakest Link]]'' and ''[[Dog Eat Dog (game show)|Dog Eat Dog]]''. NBC would find success in 2005 with a remake of another BBC series, [[The Office (US TV series)|''The Office'']], which aired for nine seasons.\n\nBecause of what was deemed to be indecent content, two affiliates of NBC refused to air the program; [[KSL-TV]] (Channel 5) in [[Salt Lake City, Utah|Salt Lake City]], and [[WNDU-TV]] (Channel 16) in [[South Bend, Indiana]]. Both stations were owned by religious organizations, as KSL is owned by the [[Bonneville International]] division of the [[LDS Church]], while WNDU was at the time owned by a subsidiary of [[The University of Notre Dame]]. In those markets, [[The WB Television Network|WB affiliate]] [[KUCW|KUWB]] (channel 30) and a [[UPN]] [[digital subchannel]] of [[CBS]] affiliate [[WSBT-TV]] (channel 22.2, now affiliated with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]), respectively, aired the series after their network's primetime lineups, while nearby affiliates [[KENV]] (in [[Elko, Nevada]], now an affiliate of [[Comet (TV network)|Comet]]) and [[WISE-TV]] (in [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]], now a [[The CW|CW]] affiliate) aired the series in accordance with the rest of the network.\n\n[[Jeff Zucker]], former President and CEO of [[NBCUniversal]], later said of ''Coupling'' that it \"just sucked\".<ref name=\"Crupi0614\">{{cite news|last=Crupi |first=Anthony |title=Mormon Station Refuses NBC's 'The Playboy Club': Second time church-owned affiliate dumps a series |work=[[Adweek]] |date=June 14, 2011 |url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/mormon-station-refuses-nbcs-playboy-club-132502 |accessdate=October 15, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62RgV36Ak?url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/mormon-station-refuses-nbcs-playboy-club-132502 |archivedate=October 15, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{See also|Coupling (British TV series)#Characters}}\n* [[Colin Ferguson (actor)|Colin Ferguson]] as Patrick Maitland\n* [[Jay Harrington]] as Steve Taylor\n* [[Christopher Moynihan]] as Jeff Clancy\n* [[Lindsay Price]] as Jane Honda\n* [[Rena Sofer]] as Susan Freeman\n* [[Sonya Walger]] as Sally Harper\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#;\"| No.\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Written by\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Original airdate\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Prod.<br/>code\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=The Right One\n |DirectedBy=[[Andrew D. Weyman]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Steven Moffat]] (original UK episode: \"[[List of Coupling episodes#ep1|Flushed]]\")\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2003|09|25}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n |ProdCode=101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=Size Matters\